<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="429" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,1580,2002]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1580,1606]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[283,433,1580,1606]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Protidricerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[283,433,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Protidricerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be characterized by its entire-eyes, unlike other members of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[1295,1432,1580,1606]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ascalaphini">Ascalaphini</taxonomicName>
, which have eyes that are split by a transverse furrow. The species are generally dark grey or black, with hyaline wings, the anal area of the forewing with weakly or distinctly produced triangular projection and the apical area beyond Sc+R vein has three rows of cells.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="429" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,1580,2002]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1724,1750]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Note.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Jones, J. R." box="[271,417,1724,1751]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" pagination="761 - 782" refId="ref26429" refString="Jones, J. R. (2019) Total-evidence phylogeny of the owlflies (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) supports a new higher-level classification. Zoologica Scripta, 48, 761 - 782. [BotN ref  18757] https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zsc. 12382" type="journal article" year="2019">Jones (2019)</bibRefCitation>
remarked that the traditional concept of entire or divided-eye is no longer the distinctive characteristics to differentiate between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[598,732,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ascalaphini">Ascalaphini</taxonomicName>
&amp; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1853" box="[772,929,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplogleniini">Haplogleniini</taxonomicName>
, as the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1094,1244,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Protidricerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1094,1244,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Protidricerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits the distinctive feature of well-developed pleurostoma, a small facial sclerite previously only encountered in divided‚Äêeye owlflies. Although we followed the new classification system proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Gillung, J. P. &amp; Winterton, S. L. &amp; Garzon-Orduna, I. J. &amp; Lemmon, A. R. &amp; Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D." box="[1007,1260,1832,1858]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" pagination="418 - 450" refId="ref26990" refString="Machado, R. J. P., Gillung, J. P., Winterton, S. L., Garzon-Orduna, I. J., Lemmon, A. R., Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D. (2019) Owlflies are derived antlions: anchored phylogenomics supports a new phylogeny and classification of Myrmeleontidae (Neuroptera). Systematic Entomology, 44, 418 - 450. [BotN ref  18370] https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12334" type="journal article" year="2019">
Machado 
<emphasis box="[1119,1177,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
for our present manuscript, the exact placement of this genus in the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1853" box="[793,947,1868,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplogleniini">Haplogleniini</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jones, J. R." box="[961,1090,1868,1894]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" refId="ref26370" refString="Jones, J. R. (2014) Taxonomic revisions of six genera of entire-eyed owlflies (Ascalaphidae: Haplogleniinae), and first largescale phylogeny of the owlflies. Ph. D. dissertation, Texas A &amp; M University, College Station, Texas, xiv + 1088 pp. [BotN ref  15994]" type="book" year="2014">Jones 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Jones, J. R." box="[1101,1159,1868,1894]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" pagination="761 - 782" refId="ref26429" refString="Jones, J. R. (2019) Total-evidence phylogeny of the owlflies (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) supports a new higher-level classification. Zoologica Scripta, 48, 761 - 782. [BotN ref  18757] https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zsc. 12382" type="journal article" year="2019">2019</bibRefCitation>
) or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[1201,1335,1868,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ascalaphini">Ascalaphini</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Gillung, J. P. &amp; Winterton, S. L. &amp; Garzon-Orduna, I. J. &amp; Lemmon, A. R. &amp; Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D." pageId="28" pageNumber="429" pagination="418 - 450" refId="ref26990" refString="Machado, R. J. P., Gillung, J. P., Winterton, S. L., Garzon-Orduna, I. J., Lemmon, A. R., Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D. (2019) Owlflies are derived antlions: anchored phylogenomics supports a new phylogeny and classification of Myrmeleontidae (Neuroptera). Systematic Entomology, 44, 418 - 450. [BotN ref  18370] https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12334" type="journal article" year="2019">
Machado 
<emphasis box="[185,241,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
) remains uncertain and must be resolved in future studies. 
<taxonomicName box="[954,1104,1904,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Protidricerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[954,1104,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Protidricerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only entire-eyed owlfly genus in the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[346,480,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ascalaphini">Ascalaphini</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[513,612,1940,1966]" name="Pakistan" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
. It includes seven described species that are distributed in the Central, East and South Asia (
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Gillung, J. P. &amp; Winterton, S. L. &amp; Garzon-Orduna, I. J. &amp; Lemmon, A. R. &amp; Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D." box="[335,572,1976,2002]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" pagination="418 - 450" refId="ref26990" refString="Machado, R. J. P., Gillung, J. P., Winterton, S. L., Garzon-Orduna, I. J., Lemmon, A. R., Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D. (2019) Owlflies are derived antlions: anchored phylogenomics supports a new phylogeny and classification of Myrmeleontidae (Neuroptera). Systematic Entomology, 44, 418 - 450. [BotN ref  18370] https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12334" type="journal article" year="2019">
Machado 
<emphasis box="[448,505,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
